{{For|the Turing Award Lecture|Turing Award}} {{Infobox award | name = BCS / IET Turing Lecture | image = Alan Turing Aged 16.jpg | image_size = <!-- or | image_upright = --> | alt = | caption = The Turing Lecture is named in honour of [[Alan Turing]], often considered the father of [[Computer Science]] | description = | sponsor = {{Plainlist| * [[Institution of Engineering and Technology|IET]] * [[British Computer Society|BCS]]}} | date = {{start date|1998}} | location = {{Plainlist| * [[London]] *[[Manchester]] * [[Cardiff]] * [[Belfast]] *[[Glasgow]]}} | country = [[United Kingdom]] | website = {{URL|http://www.bcs.org/category/5826}} |}}The '''BCS / IET Turing Lecture''' is an annual lecture given by a noted speaker on the subject of [[Computer Science]]. The lecture is delivered in several different locations annually including: The [[Royal Institution]] in London, [[Cardiff University]], The [[University of Manchester]], [[Belfast City Hall]] and the [[University of Glasgow]].<ref name=bscturing>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409072033/http://www.bcs.org/category/5951|archivedate=2015-04-09|url=http://www.bcs.org/category/5951|title=Past BCS & IET Turing Lectures|publisher=[[British Computer Society]]|location=London}}</ref><ref name=ieturing>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906071606/http://conferences.theiet.org/turing/speaker/previous/index.cfm|archivedate=2015-09-06|url=http://conferences.theiet.org/turing/speaker/previous/index.cfm|title=Previous IET and BCS Turing Lectures|publisher=[[Institution of Engineering and Technology (professional society)|Institution of Engineering and Technology]]|location=London}}</ref>
The lecture is named in honour of [[Alan Turing]], and is co-hosted by the [[British Computer Society|British Computer Society (BCS)]] and the [[Institution of Engineering and Technology (professional society)|Institution of Engineering and Technology (IET)]]. The event should not be confused with the [[Turing Award]] lecture organised by the [[Association for Computing Machinery|Association for Computing Machinery (ACM)]].<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Milner | first1 = Robin|authorlink=Robin Milner | doi = 10.1145/151233.151240 | title = Elements of interaction: Turing award lecture | journal = Communications of the ACM | volume = 36 | pages = 78–89 | year = 1993 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> Recent Turing lectures are available as a live [[webcast]] and archived online.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}
==Turing lectures== Turing lecturers have included:
* 2018: [[Andy Harter]], Innovation and technology – art or science?<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bcs.org/category/19223|title=BCS/IET Turing Lecture 2018}}</ref> * 2017: Guruduth Banavar, Beneficial [[Artificial Intelligence|AI]] for the Advancement of Humankind<ref name=banavar>{{YouTube|id=zHXJpwddeo0|title=London Turing Lecture 2017}}, [[British Computer Society]]</ref> * 2016: Robert Schukai, The Internet of Me: It's all about my screens * 2015: [[Robert Pepper]], The Internet Paradox: How bottom-up beat(s) command and control<ref>{{YouTube|lSYpimUE9tk|The IET & BCS Turing Lecture 2015: The Internet Paradox}}</ref> * 2014: Bernard S. Meyerson, Beyond silicon: Cognition and much, much more * 2013: [[Suranga Chandratillake]], What they didn't teach me: building a technology company and taking it to market * 2012: Ray Dolan,<ref name=dolanswho>{{Who's Who | author=Anon|surname = DOLAN | othernames = Prof. Raymond Joseph | id = U245952 | year= 2015 | edition = online [[Oxford University Press]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> From cryptanalysis to cognitive neuroscience – a hidden legacy of Alan Turing * 2011: [[Donald Knuth]], An Evening with Donald Knuth – All Questions Answered. * 2010: [[Christopher Bishop]]. Embracing Uncertainty: the new machine intelligence * 2009: [[J. Michael Brady]],<ref name=bradyturing>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329124424/http://www.bcs.org/category/7358|publisher=[[British Computer Society]]|title=Professor Sir Michael Brady|location=London|archivedate=2016-03-29|url=http://www.bcs.org/category/7358}}</ref> Information Engineering and its Future * 2008: [[James Martin (author)|James Martin]], Target Earth and the meaning of the 21st century * 2007: [[Grady Booch]], The Promise, the Limits and the Beauty of Software * 2006: Chris Mairs,<ref name=mairswho>{{Who's Who | author=Anon|surname = MAIRS | othernames = Christopher John | id = U245228 | year= 2015 | edition = online [[Oxford University Press]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Lifestyle access for the disabled * 2005: [[Fred Brooks]], Collaboration and Telecollaboration in Design * 2004: Fred Piper, Cyberspace Security, The Good, The Bad & The Ugly * 2003: Carol Kovac, Computing in the Age of the Genome * 2002: [[Mark Welland]], Smaller, faster, better – but is it nanotechnology? * 2001: [[Nick Donofrio]], Technology, Innovation and the New Economy * 2000: [[Brian Randell]], Facing up to Faults * 1999: [[Samson Abramsky]] From Computation to Interaction – Towards a Science of Information
